  "texts": [
    "Many filters have been designed to suppress the unwanted noise when calculating derivatives of eye tracker signals (Engelken et al., 1982; Inchingolo & Spanio, 1985; Engelken & Stevens, 1990; Das et al., 1996; Nyström & Holmqvist, 2010).",
    "Finally, data loss may occur in eye tracking signals, presenting as gaps in the eye tracking data.",
    "Gucciardi et al. (2022) present a filter for the filling of gaps in eye tracking signals, but it should be noted that many event classification algorithms also include procedures for such gap filling (e.g., Hessels et al., 2017; van Renswoude et al., 2018).",
    "Eye tracking measures such as saccade amplitude and gaze direction may be reported by the eye tracker or the tools one uses in various units, such as pixels and millimeters, but are normally reported in degrees (e.g., following the guidelines of Dunn et al., 2023, for reporting eye-and vision-related quantities).",
    "If the angle in question is below 10°, then converting from pixels or millimeters to degrees is simple."
  ],
